7.4 Copying, killing, yanking a rectangular region
==================================================

A rectangle can be copied or killed, then yanked somewhere else.

   Select a region, press вАШ<insert>вАЩ, then:
   вАҐ вАШcвАЩ to copy
   вАҐ вАШkвАЩ to kill
   вАҐ вАШyвАЩ to yank (aka paste)

   This is similar to the вАШEmacsвАЩ standard rectangle handling:
   вАҐ вАШC-x r rвАЩ copy rectangle to register
   вАҐ вАШC-x r kвАЩ kill rectangle
   вАҐ вАШC-x r yвАЩ yank killed rectangle

   The first difference is that вАШUnilineвАЩ rectangles, when killed and
yanked, do not move surrounding characters.

   The second difference is that the white characters of the yanked
rectangle are considered transparent.  As a result, only non-blank parts
of the yanked rectangle are over-printed.

   вАШUnilineвАЩ and вАШEmacsвАЩ standard rectangle share the same storage for
copied and killed rectangles, namely the вАШkilled-rectangleвАЩ Lisp
variable.  So, a rectangle can be killed one way, and yanked another
way.


