   A base drawing can be converted to dashed lines.  Moreover, lines can
be made either thin or thick.

   вАҐ Select the rectangular area you want to operate on (with mouse drag
     or вАШS-<left>вАЩ, вАШS-<down>вАЩ and so on as described earlier).
   вАҐ Type вАШINSвАЩ, then вАШsвАЩ (as "style").

   You will be offered a choice of styles:
   вАҐ вАШ3вАЩ: vertical lines will become 3 dashes per character, while
     horizontal ones will get 2 dashes per character.
   вАҐ вАШ4вАЩ: vertical and horizontal lines will get 4 dashes per character.
   вАҐ вАШhвАЩ: thin lines corners, which are usually rounded, become hard
     angles.
   вАҐ вАШ+вАЩ: thin lines and intersections become thick, empty glyphs get
     filled.
   вАҐ вАШ-вАЩ: thick lines and intersections become thin, filled glyphs are
     emptied.
   вАҐ вАШ=вАЩ: thick and thin lines become double lines.
   вАҐ вАШ0вАЩ: come back to standard base-line вАШUnilineвАЩ style: plain,
     not-dashed lines, thin corner rounded, ASCII art is converted to
     UNICODE.
   вАҐ вАШaвАЩ: apply the вАШaa2u-rectangleвАЩ function from the unrelated
     вАШascii-art-to-unicodeвАЩ package, to convert ASCII art to UNICODE
     (this only works if вАШascii-art-to-unicodeвАЩ is already installed).

   Converting parts of a drawing from one style to another can produce
nice looking sketches.




