10.1 Recommended fonts
======================

Not all fonts are born equal.

   вАҐ вАШ(set-frame-font "DejaVu Sans Mono" )вАЩ
   вАҐ вАШ(set-frame-font "Unifont" )вАЩ
   вАҐ вАШ(set-frame-font "Hack" )вАЩ
   вАҐ вАШ(set-frame-font "JetBrains Mono" )вАЩ
   вАҐ вАШ(set-frame-font "Cascadia Mono" )вАЩ
   вАҐ вАШ(set-frame-font "Agave" )вАЩ
   вАҐ вАШ(set-frame-font "JuliaMono" )вАЩ
   вАҐ вАШ(set-frame-font "FreeMono" )вАЩ
   вАҐ вАШ(set-frame-font "Iosevka Comfy Fixed" )вАЩ
   вАҐ вАШ(set-frame-font "Iosevka Comfy Wide Fixed")вАЩ
   вАҐ вАШ(set-frame-font "Aporetic Sans Mono" )вАЩ
   вАҐ вАШ(set-frame-font "Aporetic Serif Mono" )вАЩ
   вАҐ вАШ(set-frame-font "Source Code Pro" )вАЩ

   Those fonts are known to support the required UNICODE characters, AND
display them as mono-space.  There are fonts advertised as mono-space
which give arbitrary widths to non-ASCII characters.  That is bad for
the kind of drawings done by вАШUnilineвАЩ.

   You may want to try any of the suggested fonts.  Just hit the
corresponding entry in the вАШUnilineвАЩ menu, or type вАШ<insert> fвАЩ.  You
may also execute the above Lisp commands like that:

   вАШM-: (set-frame-font "DejaVu Sans Mono")вАЩ

   This setting is for the current session only.  If you want to make it
permanent, you may use the вАШEmacsвАЩ customization:

   вАШ<insert> f *вАЩ

   or

   вАШM-x customize-face defaultвАЩ

   Beware that вАШEmacsвАЩ tries to compensate for missing UNICODE support
by the current font.  вАШEmacsвАЩ substitutes one font for another,
character per character.  The user may not notice until the drawings
done under вАШEmacsвАЩ are displayed on another text editor or on the Web.
Of course, using the suggested fonts and the UNICODEs drawn by вАШUnilineвАЩ
keeps you away from those glitches.

   To know which font вАШEmacsвАЩ has chosen for a given character, type:

   вАШC-u C-x =вАЩ

   Note that none of those commands downloads a font from the Web.  The
font should already be available.


File: uniline.info,  Node: Use case mixing fonts,  Prev: Recommended fonts,  Up: Which fonts?

10.2 Use case: mixing fonts
===========================

A user on GitHub, dmullis, exposed his use-case.  A source-code base is
usually edited with a font not in the Uniline list of recommended fonts.
However, it is desirable to document the source code with Uniline,
either directly along the source or in separate files.  How to achieve
that without messing with the fonts in several Emacs buffers?

   Several solutions have emerged from the discussion.

   вАҐ вАШface-remap-add-relativeвАЩ

   A line like this at the top of the files reserved for Uniline
drawings:

     -*- eval: (face-remap-add-relative 'default :family "DejaVu Sans Mono"); -*-

   This confines its effect to just the one single buffer.

   вАҐ вАШuniline-mode-hookвАЩ

   Add a hook (a function called when entering вАШuniline-modeвАЩ):

     (add-hook
       'uniline-mode-hook
       (lambda () (face-remap-add-relative 'default :family "DejaVu Sans Mono")))

   There are also вАШuniline-mode-on-hookвАЩ & вАШuniline-mode-off-hookвАЩ which
can be handy.

   вАҐ вАШfont-lock-comment-faceвАЩ

   An alternative mean of limiting the scope of the font change is the
Emacs standard font-lock mechanism.

     (customize-face '(font-lock-comment-face))

   Then check вАШFont FamilyвАЩ, type in value вАШ"DejaVu Sans Mono",вАЩ and
вАШC-x C-sвАЩ.

   Now any major mode that understands "comments" as distinct from other
text can safely nest a Uniline drawing within its boundaries, all text
outside the "comment" unaffected (except perhaps by spacing).

   Look also at the вАШfont-lock-constant-faceвАЩ face.

   вАҐ Org Mode

   In Org Mode, the usable faces could be вАШorg-blockвАЩ, вАШorg-quoteвАЩ,
вАШorg-verseвАЩ.  But first the вАШorg-fontify-quote-and-verse-blocksвАЩ
variable must be set to вАШtвАЩ.

   вАҐ Markdown

   In Markdown mode, customize the вАШmarkdown-pre-faceвАЩ or
вАШmarkdown-code-faceвАЩ faces.


